 key issues, including the spatial geometry of the universe, inflationary versus cyclic theories of the cosmos, and the black-hole information-loss paradox. Though much progress has been made, Hawking and Penrose stress that physicists still have further to go in their quest for a quantum theory of gravity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAstrophysics. 0aCosmology. 0aQuantum theory. 0aSpace and time. 7aSCIENCE / Physics / General.2bisacsh  a2020 Nobel Prize in physics.  a2020 Nobel laureates in physics.  a2020 Nobel laureates.  aAlbert Einstein.  aAndrea Ghez.  aEinstein.  aReinhard Genzel.  aRoyal Swedish Academy of Sciences.  aStockholm.  ablack holes.  ageneral relativity.  ageneral theory of relativity.  arelativity.1 aHawking, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawking, Stephen.1 aHazvking, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPenrose, Roger, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPenrose, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPenrose, Roger.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140083474740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400834747423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400834747.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MTPY  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MTPY  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK